    <h1 style="font-size:clamp(2rem,4.5vw,2.9rem)">About</h1>
    <p>
      I’m Bruno Chikeka, a systems-oriented technologist. I analyse problems
      through the interaction of technology, institutions, incentives, and
      culture — infrastructure layers, feedback loops, and knowledge gradients
      rather than isolated events. My work sits where AI capability meets the
      physical and institutional layers that decide who it actually serves, with a
      particular focus on Africa and Alberta.
    </p>

    <h2>Now</h2>
    <p>Current focus:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Building <a href="/projects">Afrigent</a>, an AI agent platform.</li>
      <li>AI-infrastructure and sovereign-compute strategy for Alberta.</li>
      <li>An MSc dissertation on the governance of major programmes.</li>
      <li>
        <a href="/projects">Akinke</a> — AI education for African youth.
      </li>
      <li>
        Running a digital cognitive twin in the open, and keeping a public
        <a href="/ledger">prediction ledger</a>.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How this site works</h2>
    <p>
      The site is built to extend thinking, not decorate it. The
      <a href="/ledger">ledger</a> holds falsifiable predictions with locked
      probabilities and explicit disconfirmation tests; nothing is edited after
      the fact, and the machine-readable record lives in a public, commit-by-commit
      <a href="https://github.com/chiKeka/ledger">repository</a>. The
      <a href="/writing">writing</a> names its <a href="/frameworks">frameworks</a>
      so they can be challenged. If a framework stops earning its place, it gets
      retired — in public. The full scoring rules are
      <a href="/methodology">published and versioned</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Elsewhere</h2>
    <p>
      <a href="https://x.com/Chikeka">@Chikeka on X</a> ·
      <a href="https://github.com/chiKeka/ledger">Ledger repository</a>
    </p>
